You are thinking in the right direction. Your analogies are basically describing warm standby, hot standby/read replica, and multi-primary/multi-master database setups. The important missing piece is this: failover strategy is not only about “which DB is available”, it is also about data consistency, write safety, failover time, replication lag, and conflict handling.

Below is a careful analysis.

1. First, understand two key terms: RTO and RPO

Before choosing any failover strategy, always ask:

RTO: Recovery Time Objective

How long can the application be down?

Example:

If primary DB fails, can we tolerate 5 minutes downtime?
Or should failover happen in 5 seconds?

RPO: Recovery Point Objective

How much data loss is acceptable?

Example:

Can we lose last 5 seconds of transactions?
Can we lose last 1 minute?
Or should data loss be zero?


These two decide whether you need backup restore, warm standby, hot standby, synchronous replica, or multi-primary.

2. Your Strategy 1: Warm standby

Your idea:

“We will have a replica of my big DB. Once main DB is down, I will use the backup one.”

This is close to warm standby.

What it means

You have:

Application → Primary DB
                 |
                 v
             Standby DB


The standby database is not actively serving user traffic. It is waiting. If primary fails, you promote the standby.

PostgreSQL documentation describes standby servers as secondary servers that track primary changes, and a warm standby is one that is not normally connected to until it is promoted.

Good points
Simpler than multi-primary.
Lower cost than fully active-active systems.
Good for disaster recovery.
Writes happen only on one primary, so no write conflict problem.
Easier to reason about data consistency.
Problems / trade-offs
1. Failover is not instant

You need to:

Detect failure → Promote standby → Redirect traffic → Verify app works


This can take seconds to minutes depending on automation.

2. Possible data loss

If replication is asynchronous, primary may commit data that has not yet reached the standby. If the primary dies before replication catches up, that data can be lost. PostgreSQL docs mention that standby can contain “almost all” data of the main server in WAL-based standby, which implies small data gaps are possible depending on sync mode.

3. Standby capacity may be untested

If the backup DB is not serving traffic normally, you may not know whether it can handle production traffic after failover.

When to use warm standby

Use it when:

You can tolerate some failover time.
You want simpler architecture.
You mostly need disaster recovery.
Your application cannot tolerate write conflicts.
You want one clear source of truth.
3. Your Strategy 2: Hot standby / read replica

Your idea:

“I will do read operation from main and backup DB, and write to backup DB happens all the time. Once primary DB goes down, we take the replica DB.”

This is close to hot standby with read replicas.

A hot standby is a standby server that can accept connections and serve read-only queries while it follows the primary. Azure SQL failover groups also support using secondary databases for read-only workloads through read-only listener endpoints.

Typical architecture
                 ┌─────────────┐
Writes ────────> │ Primary DB   │
                 └──────┬──────┘
                        │ replication
                        v
                 ┌─────────────┐
Reads ─────────> │ Replica DB   │
                 └─────────────┘


Usually:

Writes → Primary only
Reads  → Primary or replicas

Very important correction

You wrote:

“read operation from main and backup DB as the write to backup DB happen all the time”

Better wording:

Application writes only to primary.
Primary continuously replicates changes to replica.
Application may read from replica.
If primary fails, replica is promoted.


The application should usually not write directly to the backup/replica unless it has been promoted.

Good points
1. Read scaling

You can send heavy read traffic to replicas:

Reports
Dashboards
Search pages
Analytics reads


This reduces load on the primary.

2. Faster failover than backup restore

The replica is already running and almost up to date.

3. Better production confidence

Because replica is serving reads, you know it is alive and usable.

Main problem: replication lag

This is the biggest issue.

Example:

T1: User creates order on primary.
T2: User immediately opens "My Orders".
T3: Read request goes to replica.
T4: Replica has not received latest change yet.
Result: User does not see the new order.


This happens because replicas may be slightly behind the primary.

How to handle replication lag
Option A: Read-your-writes from primary

After a user writes something, route their next few reads to primary.

POST /orders        → primary
GET /orders/latest  → primary for same user/session

Option B: Use replicas only for stale-tolerant reads

Good for:

Product catalog
Reports
Analytics
Public content
Logs


Not good for:

Bank balance
Order confirmation
Payment status
Recently updated profile

Option C: Monitor replica lag

If replica lag is high, stop sending reads to it.

if replica_lag > 2 seconds:
    route reads to primary

When to use hot standby/read replica

Use it when:

You have many reads.
Some reads can tolerate slightly stale data.
You want faster failover.
You want simpler architecture than multi-primary.

This is the most common production setup for many systems.

4. Your Strategy 3: Multi-primary / multi-master

Your idea:

“We will use 2 DB operations all the time, read and write. If one goes down, the second is always ready. But with 5 DBs, it is not good to write all the DBs. What if one write operation failed? It might take longer.”

Your concern is absolutely correct.

Multi-primary means multiple database nodes can accept writes. PostgreSQL documentation clearly says read-only database servers are easier to combine, but read/write servers are much harder because a write to any server must be propagated to all servers so future reads stay consistent.

Architecture
          ┌─────────────┐
Writes →  │ DB Node A   │
          └──────┬──────┘
                 │ sync/replication
          ┌──────▼──────┐
Writes →  │ DB Node B   │
          └──────┬──────┘
                 │
          ┌──────▼──────┐
Writes →  │ DB Node C   │
          └─────────────┘


In theory, it sounds perfect:

Any DB can read.
Any DB can write.
If one DB fails, others continue.


But in practice, it is much harder.

5. Main problems in multi-primary
Problem 1: Write conflict

Suppose two users update the same record at the same time.

DB A:
User changes account_name = "Ashutosh"

DB B:
Another request changes account_name = "Sarangi"


Now both DBs replicate to each other.

Question:

Which value is correct?
Ashutosh or Sarangi?


This is called a conflict.

In single-primary architecture, this problem is easier because all writes go through one database, so ordering is clear.

Problem 2: Partial write failure

You said:

“What if one write operation failed?”

Exactly.

Imagine writing to 5 DBs:

DB1 write success
DB2 write success
DB3 write failed
DB4 write success
DB5 timeout


Now what should happen?

You have only a few choices:

Option A: Roll back everywhere

But rollback across many databases is complex and slow.

Option B: Accept partial success

Then databases are inconsistent.

Option C: Retry failed nodes

But during retry, some reads may return old data.

Option D: Use consensus/quorum

Example:

Write is successful if 3 out of 5 nodes confirm.


This improves availability, but consistency becomes more complex.

Problem 3: Higher write latency

If every write must be confirmed by many DBs:

Client → DB1 → DB2 → DB3 → DB4 → DB5 → response


The user waits longer.

If one DB is slow, all writes may become slow.

Synchronous replication can avoid data loss because a transaction is not considered committed until required servers have committed it, but this increases latency and can reduce availability if replicas are slow or unavailable.

Problem 4: Split-brain

This is one of the most dangerous problems.

Imagine two DB nodes cannot talk to each other because of a network issue.

Region A thinks: I am primary.
Region B thinks: I am primary.


Both accept writes.

Later, network recovers.

Now you have conflicting data.

This is called split-brain.

Problem 5: Operational complexity

Multi-primary requires:

Conflict detection.
Conflict resolution.
Strong monitoring.
Replication topology management.
Careful schema migration.
Application-level idempotency.
Transaction design.
Handling network partitions.
Sometimes consensus algorithms.

For most normal applications, this is overkill.

6. Important distinction: sync vs async replication

This applies to warm standby and hot standby too.

Asynchronous replication
Primary commits write.
Primary responds to user.
Replica receives change later.

Pros
Faster writes.
Less dependency on replica.
Better performance.
Cons
Possible data loss if primary fails before replica receives latest writes.
Replica lag.
Synchronous replication
Primary commits write.
Replica confirms write.
Then primary responds to user.

Pros
Lower chance of data loss.
Better consistency.
Cons
Slower writes.
If replica is down or slow, primary may be affected.
Cross-region sync can be expensive and slow.

PostgreSQL docs describe synchronous solutions as those where a data-modifying transaction is not considered committed until all required servers have committed the transaction, which helps avoid data loss on failover but creates synchronization overhead.

7. Your three strategies compared
Strategy	Writes go to	Reads go to	Failover speed	Data loss risk	Complexity	Best forWarm standby	Primary only	Primary only	Medium	Low to medium	Low	DR, simpler HA
Hot standby/read replica	Primary only	Primary + replicas	Fast	Low to medium	Medium	Read-heavy apps
Multi-primary	Multiple DBs	Multiple DBs	Very fast	Depends on design	Very high	Global writes, advanced systems
8. What I would recommend in most real systems

For most backend systems, including FastAPI or microservice-based apps, I would recommend this:

Primary DB:
- All writes

Read Replica 1:
- Read-only traffic
- Reporting
- dashboards

Read Replica 2:
- Failover candidate
- Backup jobs


Architecture:

                  ┌──────────────┐
Write requests →  │ Primary DB    │
                  └──────┬───────┘
                         │
          ┌──────────────┴──────────────┐
          v                             v
   ┌──────────────┐              ┌──────────────┐
   │ Read Replica │              │ Failover DB  │
   └──────────────┘              └──────────────┘


Application routing:

POST/PUT/PATCH/DELETE → primary
Critical GET after write → primary
Normal GET/reporting → replicas


This gives you:

Good availability.
Better read performance.
Low complexity.
No multi-primary write conflict.
Easier failover.
9. Best practical failover design

A good production design usually includes:

1. Automated health check
Is primary reachable?
Is replication healthy?
Is replica lag acceptable?

2. Automatic or controlled promotion

If primary fails:

Promote replica → New primary

3. Stable connection endpoint

Do not hardcode database host everywhere.

Use:

db-write.myapp.internal
db-read.myapp.internal


or a cloud-managed listener/proxy. Azure SQL failover groups provide read-write and read-only listener endpoints that remain unchanged during geo-failover, so the application does not need to change the connection string after failover.

4. Prevent old primary from coming back as primary

This is called fencing.

If the old primary comes back, it should not accept writes until it is safely rejoined as a replica.

5. Test failover regularly

Do not assume failover works.

Run drills:

Kill primary
Promote replica
Check application
Check data consistency
Restore old primary as replica

10. Simple analogy

Think of the DB as a “main notebook”.

Warm standby

You have a photocopy kept in a drawer.

Main notebook is used daily.
Copy is available if main is lost.

Hot standby

You have a photocopy that is updated continuously, and people can read from it.

Main notebook is written.
Copy notebook is read by others.

Multi-primary

Five people each have notebooks and all can write.

Everyone writes independently.
Later they try to merge notes.


This sounds powerful, but conflicts become hard:

Person A wrote value = 10
Person B wrote value = 12
Which one wins?

11. Final conclusion

Your thinking is correct, especially your concern about multi-primary.

For most systems:

Best default choice = Single primary + hot standby/read replicas


Use multi-primary only when you truly need:

Multi-region writes.
Very low write latency across geographies.
Advanced conflict resolution.
Very high availability requirements.
Engineering team capable of managing the complexity.

For your notes, remember this short version:

Warm standby:
Backup DB is ready but mostly passive.

Hot standby:
Replica is continuously updated and can serve reads.

Multi-primary:
Multiple DBs accept writes, but conflict resolution and partial failure become very complex.

Most practical architecture:
One primary for writes, replicas for reads and failover.
